body:
### Description

For now, the transformation passes of arc handle the instantious work to the state op, split combinational and sequential logic part to different state op in arc. In this way, the instantiated object must be inlined, so that the passthrough function and clock_tree function can be generated smoothly. The way that tries to inline other modules has a processing advantage over generated code, but it will cause a lot of code copying behavior, which has a great negative impact on i-cache when doing simulation.

![2023-03-15_14-28](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/33774564/226229694-ce5a6754-cc3f-47e7-95f2-2a72f0bd7a73.png)

In a paper that rigorously analyzes the performances impact of various problems faced during code execution on linux. The cache-miss penalty is about 100 cycles. The excessively large code size generated by the inline method causes i-cache eviction at every simulation cycle.

This problem becomes even more obvious when simulating designs with multiple instantiations of same module such as SMP processors(such as the figure above), The same issue happens in Verilator as well as it inlines all modules in multhithreaded simulation.

### Suggestion

We could avoid inlining all modules, instead we turn each module instantiations into function call.  

The following is a example showing Verilog code to equivalent C code in our design ():

```verilog
module my_dff (
    input clk,    // Clocks are used in sequential circuits
    input d,
    output reg q );//
    always @ (posedge clk) begin
            q <= d;
    end
    // Use a clocked always block
    //   copy d to q at every positive edge of clk
    //   Clocked always blocks should use non-blocking assignments
endmodule

module Moduleshift ( input clk, input d, output q );
    wire [1:0] q_net;
    my_dff dff0 (.d(d), .clk(clk), .q(q_net[0]));
    my_dff dff1 (.d(q_net[0]), .clk(clk), .q(q_net[1]));
    my_dff dff2 (.d(q_net[1]), .clk(clk), .q(q));
endmodule
```

```c
// store trigger signal & state variables (q_reg)
// dly means delay, which represents the last cycle state
typedef struct {
  int clk, last_clk;
  int d;
  int q_reg;
  int dly_q_reg;
} st_my_dff;

// store struct pointers that are used to transfer states
// to instantious modules
typedef struct {
  st_my_dff *dff0, dff1, dff2;

  int clk;
  int d;
  int q;
} st_Moduleshift;

// main body of my_dff
void my_dff(st_my_dff *_s) {
  if (_s->clk & (~_s->last_clk)) {
    _s->q_reg = _s->d;
  }
  _s->last_clk = _s->clk;

}

// main body of Moduleshift
void Moduleshift(st_Moduleshift *_s) {
  _s->dff0->clk = _s->clk;
  _s->dff0->d = _s->d;
  _s->dff1->clk = _s->clk;
  _s->dff1->d = _s->dff0->dly_q_reg;
  _s->dff2->clk = _s->clk;
  _s->dff2->d = _s->dff1->dly_q_reg;
  my_dff(_s->dff0);
  my_dff(_s->dff1);
  my_dff(_s->dff2);
  _s->q = _s->dff2->dly_q_reg;

  // redundant when always stmt no active.
  _s->dff0->dly_q_reg = _s->dff0->q_reg;
  _s->dff1->dly_q_reg = _s->dff1->q_reg;
  _s->dff2->dly_q_reg = _s->dff2->q_reg;

}

// In Top layer to evaluate modules
void eval() {
  static st_Moduleshift _Moduleshift;
  Moduleshift(&_Moduleshift);
}

// void init(){}
```

### Addition

I just speculated and analyzed the current simulation path of arc. If there is anything wrong or there is a problem with the analysis, please point it out. I will be very happy for such an exchange opportunity.
